AGI -&nbsp;The President of the Council, Giorgia Meloni, leaves the EU's extraordinary summit on defence and Ukraine with some satisfaction. Italy has brought home several results for the financing of the defense but asks more: the suspension of the Stability and Growth Pact, which recognizes elements of perplexity already reported by Italy in the past, must not be limited to the expenses of defence; as it is excluded that Italy can hijack the funds of Coesione to the rearmament. Word that among other things the premier does not share, defines it ' unhappy' because it transmits a wrong message to citizens and limits the broad concept of defence and security to weapons.
&nbsp;
"We have conducted a battle to exclude cohesion funds, i.e. to exclude the possibility that resources from the cohesion funds will be forced to hijack. There has been a clause for which nations can make this choice voluntarily," Meloni explained. "Callingly, we cannot prevent other nations from making this choice, especially those which are most exposed, but for what I am proposing to Parliament to clarify immediately that Italy does not intend to hijack cohesion funds, they are very important funds for us, on the purchase of weapons. And this will of course be a decision that we will then take together with Parliament, surely it will be the proposal that I will carry on," he said.
<div </div
Another question on the table at the Twenty-seven meeting concerns the debt problem. Most of the proposals in the ReArm Eu plan are in fact based on the new debt of the States, although scorped by the deficit and favoured in part by the common loan of 150 billion. The President of the Council has commissioned the Minister of Economy, Giancarlo Giorgetti, to present already to the next Ecofin a proposal to establish a European guarantee to promote investments in the field, thus focusing on private funds, as happens with InvestEu. "Callingly, when nations like ours approach debt, there are risks that must be taken into account," he said.
&nbsp;
Meloni - who has collected a lot of interest on the proposal to convene a Ue-Usa summit on the future of Kiev - reiterates that he finds "complete and ineffective" the proposal to send troops to Ukrainian territory as a security guarantee, would prefer the extension of article 5 of NATO (without of course membership) to the country.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"I think that the obviously central issue of peace in Ukraine, on which I think we must make all possible efforts to foster a peace process, clearly greeting favorably, from the American initiative, all those who want to arrive at a peace process. But just peace needs certain security guarantees. The security guarantees I think are always in the hive of the Atlantic alliance, the only serious way to guarantee them is that, then there are several ways to do so in which we are carrying out our proposals but I think that to send unidentified troops, European troops then, in short, French, British, is the most complex and perhaps the least effective solution. I said it and I reiterated it. I have also excluded the possibility that in this framework Italian soldiers can be sent and I think that we must also think about solutions more lasting than those that could represent today a dispatch of troops", he explained.
&nbsp;
"Other topic is the issues of UN peacekeeping missions but it is all other matter because they are missions that intervene when there is a peace process started and it is not the proposal that is being discussed these hours," he said. For Meloni an extension of Article 5 of NATO "would be much more effective, it would be a stable, lasting, effective security guarantee".
&nbsp;
The President of the Council once again reiterated his point of arrival: "A solution that can be effective and serious because we have fought for it in these three years. All the efforts we have made were to reach a just peace, a peace that had rules and today that there are conditions thanks to that work. Because if we hadn't supported Ukraine today we wouldn't be talking about peace, I remind everyone that they say it's us, even that it's me that I unleashed the war in Ukraine, I've heard these crazy things say. We have worked banally because there was no invasion of Ukraine, so that Ukraine would remain standing and that there would be adequate conditions to sit at the table. Today we have arrived at that moment and we must harvest the fruits of the sacrifices we have made." &nbsp;
